      "title": "A novel optimal filter design for the improved dynamic performance of 3-phase PLLs for phase tracking under grid imperfections",
      "link": "http://www.stanford.edu/~sambhav/research",
      "start_date": null,
      "end_date": null,
      "description": "• Analysed and modelled the existing 3-phase PLL schemes augmented on a synchronous reference frame (SRF) PLL, built to track frequency and phase fluctuations of a disturbed grid• Identified two major limitations with the traditional Wiener method of loop filter design: (i) yields non-optimum solution due to the inverse dependency between filtering characteristic and dynamic response (ii) requires cumbersome trial-and-error in filter parameter selection• Devised a mathematically rigorous direct analytic approach (i) to eliminate the inherent trade-off in filter parameter selection by decoupling filtering and fast tracking (ii) to yield unique filter parameters for faster tracking, thus achieving the best fit without relying on trial-and-error• Validated the proposed methodology through extensive comparisons in simulation and experiments on a laboratory setup (paper submitted for peer-review)",
